{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503831"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:07:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:07:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2087"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2087"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.05,0.3,0.12,0.52]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2087"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101369"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2087"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2087"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83799"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"822"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10201"},{"type":"tags","id":"10203"},{"type":"tags","id":"11383"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34774"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35007"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35205"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101369"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a sore left arm following a fall off his road bike five days ago. X-rays confirm an uncomplicated distal radius fracture.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the bone healing process that is beginning to occur at this stage?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Resorption of excess bony callus","Formation of a hard callus suitable for weight bearing","Creation of a haematoma by ruptured blood vessels, which fills the fracture gap","Endochondral ossification of newly formed collagen along the fracture line","Stimulation of osteoclastic and osteoblastic activity with soft tissue callus formation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFive days after a fracture, the bone healing process would be in the early proliferative phase. The correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Estimulation of osteoclastic and osteoblastic activity with soft tissue callus formation\u003C/strong\u003E. At this stage, osteoclasts begin to remove damaged bone while osteoblasts start to produce new bone matrix, forming a soft callus (also called procallus) that consists primarily of fibrous tissue and cartilage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options represent other stages of bone healing:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EResorption of excess bony callus\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs during the remodeling phase, which begins weeks to months after the fracture and can continue for years. During this phase, excess callus is removed and the bone is reshaped to its original contour.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of a hard callus suitable for weight bearing\u003C/strong\u003E - Hard callus formation occurs 2-3 weeks after fracture when the soft callus mineralizes through the deposition of calcium hydroxyapatite. This provides mechanical rigidity to the healing fracture.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECreation of a haematoma by ruptured blood vessels, which fills the fracture gap\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the initial phase that occurs immediately after fracture (within hours). Blood vessels in the periosteum, bone marrow, and surrounding tissues rupture, forming a haematoma that serves as a scaffold for repair.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndochondral ossification of newly formed collagen along the fracture line\u003C/strong\u003E - This process occurs later, typically 2-3 weeks after injury, when cartilage in the soft callus is replaced by bone through a process similar to endochondral bone formation during development.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe typical sequence of bone healing is: haematoma formation (hours) \u2192 inflammatory phase (days 1-3) \u2192 soft callus formation (days 4-14) \u2192 hard callus formation (weeks 2-6) \u2192 bone remodeling (weeks to years).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bone healing begins with haematoma formation immediately after fracture.","The inflammatory phase occurs within the first few days, with recruitment of inflammatory cells.","By day 5, soft tissue callus formation begins with osteoclastic and osteoblastic activity.","Hard callus formation and remodeling occur in later stages of fracture healing."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas A, Aster J, Robbins S. Robbins and Cotran\u0027s pathologic basis of disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2014. (Chapter 26, Topic \u2018Bones, Joints and Soft Tissue tumours\u2019)","Sheen JR, Mabrouk A, Garla VV. Fracture Healing Overview. [Updated 2023 Apr 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK551678/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83799"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2087"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83799"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-